post_text: The TLCS Charter Board is looking for a new parent representative. We are an organization representing the different stakeholder groups at the school: teachers, support staff, district board, and parents. We are looking for a parent who is willing to seek input from, and listen to, TLCS families. The time commitment would be a minimum of one board meeting a month. We also have occasional work sessions, and project committee opportunities. If you are interested in serving, please send a letter of interest to Dwight Coon, district board president at the school’s address (20264 Blachly Grange Rd. Blachly, OR 97412).

post_text:
TLCS Community:

We are working on a plan for what Fall 2020-2021 will look like. As you know, we have been dealing with complications/impacts from the pandemic since March. We initially provided Supplemental Education (which was review learning), and then moved into Distance Learning For All. During closure, we provide thousands of meals to students, checked out technology, and continued learning opportunities.

Last week, the Oregon Department of Education (ODE) provided an initial guidance document and we have to develop a plan that will need to be reviewed by our county health department, approved by the Board of Education, and a final application for reopening submitted to ODE by August 15.

We have 3 models to explore for the Fall: all on-site, all distance, or a hybrid of the two. There are comprehensive safety and cleaning protocols and specific parameters that must be met. As we work through what makes sense for TLCS and what we can realistically implement, we will be asking for your input. Please watch for surveys coming out very soon!

Best, Ms. K

Click the link to see ODE guidance and resources about next year: https://www.oregon.gov/ode/students-and-family/healthsafety/Pages/Planning-for-the-2020-21-School-Year.aspx

Today is the last day of school for the 2019-2020 school year. It has been a wild and weird spring term, and we thank you for your patience and partnership as we worked together to continue learning experiences and connection for all our students.
We are sad that we don't get to close out the year with hugs and high-fives. But, know that we are thinking about all of you and will miss you over the summer break!
~Ms. K

An incredibly huge THANK YOU to the Florence Masonic Lodge and two anonymous donors! Their generous donations allowed us to give every K-5th grade student a BOOK A MONTH. Over 725 books and over 40 different titles went home with our elementary students this year.

The books pictured are being sent home to students this month! Some new books to enjoy as we kick off the K-5 Principal’s Summer Reading Challenge. Reading challenge forms are also being sent home this week.

If you would like additional information please contact Sadie Mooney at smooney@blachly.k12.or.us. HAPPY READING!

Dear Class of 2020:
Today would have been your graduation day - and we are with you in spirit (from a distance) as we celebrate all that you have accomplished over the last 13 years! I am so proud of who you have become, and what you have achieved. I look forward to watching your future unfold, and hope you will come back to TLCS to visit and keep us updated on your new adventures. I expect great things from you, and have no doubts that you will continue to make us proud. #LakerPride
~Ms. K

shared_text:
Benjamin Ruppel‎Triangle Lake Charter School
May 8 at 11:14 AM ·

This week is teacher appreciation week. I made a post awhile ago in jest due to COVID-19. I could never take a place of our teachers. They have the skills of patience, listening, acknowledging and finding the switch to turn the light bulb on for each student. Our teachers have been forced to not only teach students but teach parents on how to teach. I am enjoying the time I have with my daughter but to multiply that by a bunch is insane. In a world full of division and competition I appreciate our teachers who want to bring the best out of every student no matter what. Thank you Mrs. Robertson for your great videos, and to the rest of the teachers for their hard work!! #GoLakersTLCS!

post_text:
TLCS Community:
With the extended school closure until April 28, the following planned events will also be CANCELED:

-After school clubs and activities
-Athletic practices and competitions
-Field trips and guest speakers
-Ashland trip
-Junior/Senior banquet
-Kindergarten information night - may be rescheduled
-All TSP events that would have happened on campus during this time
-Mountain West Music Festival - we will not be attending unless it is rescheduled for a later time
-Mr. Laker Pageant
-Outdoor School - This is being rescheduled for late May, if possible. Watch for more details

Events that are scheduled to happen after the planned return 4/28 will be addressed as we get closer to that time. Additional events may need to be canceled, postponed, or rescheduled.

We have had many families ask about what education will look like. Please know that we are working as quickly as we can to develop a plan with guidance from ODE, and will communicate that out to you as soon as possible.

post_text:
Board Meeting Update: In light of today's new guidance, this week's public board meetings will be provided in an online GoToMeeting platform. This means that an individual might attend the board meeting from home. It will also allow us to implement the "no groups larger than 25" directive from the Governor. We will set up computers in classrooms so that we can spread out and do not have any single gathering that goes over that threshold. Login information will be shared tomorrow morning. If there are less than 25 people at either meeting, we will spread out in the library to appropriate social distances (3-6 feet).

Agendas can be found here: http://www.blachly.k12.or.us/closure-public-meetings/

In accordance with this evening’s guidance and in order to minimize potential opportunities for the virus to spread, ALL AFTER-SCHOOL ACTIVITIES AND MEETINGS FOR THURSDAY MARCH 12, 2020 ARE CANCELED.
More information for a longer-term plan will be released after additional guidance is provided, during the day on March 12th. Check back for details.

post_text:
We are monitoring the situation with COVID-19 closely, and taking guidance from Oregon Department of Education (ODE) and Oregon Health Authority (OHA).
We are increasing cleaning and disinfecting throughout the school.
Please encourage your child to practice healthy habits such as covering coughs and sneezes, avoid touching their face, and regular hand-washing.
Keep your child home if they are sick. Students need to be fever-free for 24 hours, without the use of fever-reducing medication, before returning to school.
Reach out to your doctor if you or your child have symptoms of COVID-19 or you have questions about symptoms.

post_text: Reminder: community input meeting on qualities for the new superintendent is Tuesday 3/10 at 6pm!
shared_text:
Triangle Lake Charter School
March 3 at 6:05 PM ·

We are working with a superintendent search consultant agency as we begin the process for hiring a new superintendent. The consultants will be facilitating a community input meeting on **Tuesday March 10, 2020 @ 6pm in the library.**
Please join them and provide your input about the desired qualities for a new superintendent who will begin employment July 1, 2020.

Please also complete the survey at: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/Blachly_Search_Questionnaire2020
The survey will only take about 5 minutes and responses are collected by the Search Consultant. The survey will close at 5pm on 3/12.

With the information gathered at the meetings and from the online survey the School Board will adopt a set of qualifications for the 2020 superintendent search. The School Board anticipates discussing the information at its board meeting March 18, 2020, where the public will have a chance to offer comments before the Board adopts a set of qualifications for the position.

We are working with a superintendent search consultant agency as we begin the process for hiring a new superintendent. The consultants will be facilitating a community input meeting on **Tuesday March 10, 2020 @ 6pm in the library.**
Please join them and provide your input about the desired qualities for a new superintendent who will begin employment July 1, 2020.

Please also complete the survey at: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/Blachly_Search_Questionnaire2020
The survey will only take about 5 minutes and responses are collected by the Search Consultant. The survey will close at 5pm on 3/12.

With the information gathered at the meetings and from the online survey the School Board will adopt a set of qualifications for the 2020 superintendent search. The School Board anticipates discussing the information at its board meeting March 18, 2020, where the public will have a chance to offer comments before the Board adopts a set of qualifications for the position.

post_text:
Hello all-

The fall season has come to an end with great success and fan-fare.

The Lady Lakers finished the season just out of volleyball playoff contention. A great season nonetheless. The Lady Lakers were fun to watch.
Our high school cross country team (Cosie) did well at districts, but did not make it into the top five, which would've qualified her for the state meet.
The middle school cross country team did well this season, and it sounds as if they had a fun time doing it.
The high school football team lost just one game all season. They finished 3rd in the state 6-man playoff at Madras Saturday.
The middle school volleyball team finished second in league in a playoff nail-biter. The final game went to the third match and was decided by who had the last serve.
The middle school football team went undefeated! The last game of the season was at Eddyville against an undefeated Eagle team. We won decidedly.
Great job to all the Laker teams!

Go Lakers!

--
Tony Wynn

All students (K-12) are allowed to wear a costume to school on Halloween 🎃as long as they follow these guidelines:
-Costumes must be safe, appropriate for school, and not distracting from learning.
-No weapons (real or fake) or bloody gore (must be appropriate for kindergarten students to see).
-Students must be able to do their regularly scheduled school activities.
-Student faces must be visible.

post_text:
Cross Country
Cross Country is available to grades 5th – 12th. We will begin practicing together Tuesday, August 20th from 4:00 to 5:00 pm. We will practice Tuesday-Thursday that week and Monday-Thursday the following week. When school begins we will practice after school Monday-Thursday. If you have not already been running, you should begin now. Our first meet will be The Ultimook in Tillamook, OR Saturday, September 7th. We will leave for this meet on Friday and camp out and run Saturday morning. Athletes must be up to date on their physicals in order to participate in practices and meets. Physicals need to be done every two years. Please check with the school if you are not sure whether your child needs their physical. If you have any questions, please email me at pwynn@blachly.k12.or.us. Thank you. Mrs. Wynn.

Information pertaining to fall sports from Athletic Director, Tony Wynn:

• Pay to play fees are $75 for high school and $60 for middle school. Scholarships and payment plans are available—see Tony Wynn for details.
• All paperwork needs to be completed by the first contest.

post_text: Each month the first graders are measuring the depth of the water, Mr. Jeff’s shadow, the air temperature and the water temperature. CALENDAR UPDATE:
Friday April 12th and Friday May 17th will be SCHOOL days for all K-12 students.
These days were reserved on the calendar published at the beginning of the year, and are being added back to make up for lost days due to weather closures.
The school board officially approved this change at the board meeting last week. Fliers will be sent home with students after spring break.
